nt|^b@2^z@3

|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at| Paul Hackett was a World Grandmaster back in the 1950's and still plays for the Great Britain Senior Team. Justin and Jason are now both World International Masters have for some time been two of the highest-ranked UK players in the WBF rankings list. 

I stopped playing Face-to-Face Bridge in about 1991 when I met my wife Naomi (who doesn't play).  I now play and teach entirely online on BBO.

Today's session is more of an introduction to Precision than anything else and we'll not be getting into many specifics. 

The schedule for the sessions is detailed on my Precision website and can be seen at ^*h http://ocp.pigpen.org.uk/Program.php ^*n. 

Before we start there are a few things that need to be said. At it's simplest, Precision is a fairly "natural" system and no more difficult to learn than, for example, Standard American or Acol. 

However, a normal progression would be to have a reasonably thorough grounding in one of those systems before moving on to a system like Precision. The reason for this is that Precision is very much a D-I-Y system in that it lends itself to more complex additions.

The system I teach is NOT REMOTELY "Standard" let alone "Basic" Precision, but a somewhat simplified version of the system I developed and played in the 1970's and 1980's and is more accurately called "Super-Precision".

The system I teach includes numerous additions to and variations of Standard Precision (which you are free to ignore, of course) that give the system enormous power. This system is not for the faint-hearted, however, and it is definitely not a system for beginners.

If you have not already done so, please have a look at the notes I have prepared on Precision Club bidding. You can find these on: ^*h http://ocp.pigpen.org.uk ^*n You might want to have these onscreen in the background for reference during the session.|
