|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Ok, Let's take a look at the Opening Bids in the "Classic" version of Precision. I stress that these are NOT exactly what I teach, but I am showing you them just so that you can see where the differences lie.
This IS "Standard Precision", but it's NOT what I teach ^c@2

1@C ^d Any hand with 16+ points except 20-22 balanced (2NT).
1@D ^d 11-15, No 5-card Major, No 6-card Clubs, Not 13-15 balanced.
1@H ^d 11-15, 5-card or longer Hearts, Spades shorter than Hearts.
1@S ^d 11-15, 5-card or longer Spades, Hearts not longer.
1NT ^d 13-15 balanced or semi-balanced with a 5-card Minor.
      
2@C ^d 11-15, 6-card or longer Clubs, or 5-card Clubs with a 4-card Major.
2@D ^d 11-15, 4414 shape with a singleton Diamond.
2@H ^d 5-9 with a 6-card Heart suit.
2@S ^d 5-9 with a 6-card Spade suit.
2NT ^d 20-22 balanced.

^b@2The 1@D Opening is always a catch-all Opening showing 11-15 points and a hand unsuitable for any of the other intermediate Openings. 3 and 4-level Openings are fairly standard (ie: similar to Standard American). 

The Opening Bid most often "tinkered with" is the 2@D Opening. Most Precision pairs absorb that hand-type into the 1@D Opening and use 2@D for something else (eg: Multi, Weak 2, etc). 

Precision (and indeed most strong club systems) enjoy two huge advantages over systems such as Standard American, Acol, 2/1 etc in which the range for an Opening 1-level bid is typically 11-20 points. 

This puts pressure on responder to come up with a response in case partner is very strong. 

So playing 2/1 or Standard American and you have a grotty 5 or 6-count and your partner opens 1@S and you hold something like  @Sxx, @HKxxx, @DQxx, @CJxxx,  you are pretty much FORCED to bid something in case your partner has a monster hand.
|
