|cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  In Precision, because the 1@D, 1@H, 1@S, 2@C and 2@D Openings are limited to a maximum of 15 points, responder is much better placed and can happily pass with a 7 or 8-count with nothing particular to say, knowing that it is extremely unlikely that a game is being missed.

Sequences such as  1x-pass-pass-pass are  far more common in Precision.  

So the hand I just outlined would be an automatic PASS opposite a Precision 1@S Opening Similarly, the 1@C Opening shows 16+ points, so Responder with a good hand themselves is in a much better position to know when the prospects of a slam are good.

When responder makes a positive response to 1@C, the whole sequence is immediately game-forcing.

So there is no need to make expensive, space-consuming bids to force to game. This allows much more space for slam-investigation. 

Over a Precision 1@C Opening, 1@D is a "Negative" Response showing 0-7 HCP.  

Bidding now continues entirely on a natural and non-forcing basis.  

Anything OTHER than 1@D is a "positive" response and Game-Forcing, showing 8+ HCP.  

In Precision you don't see many jump-shifts JUST to show strength.


The advantages I have just mentioned are ALONE enough to give Precision a big edge over other systems such as 2/1, Standard American and Acol.


